{
    "analysis": "We have completed loading telemetry, computing global thresholds, filtering to the incident window (2022-03-21 11:30–12:00 UTC+8), and detecting anomalies. The anomaly tables (metric_anomalies_df, trace_anomalies_df, log_anomalies_df) show many high-severity node-level metric anomalies (notably node-6, node-4, node-1, node-2) and numerous container/network/IO anomalies tied to nodes. Earliest high-severity timestamps observed include 1647833400 (node-4 tcp retransmits), 1647833460 (node-1/node-2 tcp retransmits), and 1647834000 (node-6 IO spikes). Per the diagnosis rules, node-level faults show the largest deviations (>>50%) so the root cause level is likely a node. To choose the root node we need a concise per-node summary of anomaly timing, severity, and prevalence so we can pick the most likely root node by earliest occurrence, maximum severity, and number of distinct faulty KPIs.",
