    "instruction": "Using the cached metric_anomalies_df, produce a compact node-level summary only for cmdb_id values that start with 'node-'. For each node present, compute and return these columns (one row per node): node (cmdb_id), num_anomalous_kpis (count of distinct kpi_name flagged as anomalous), earliest_anomaly_timestamp (minimum earliest_anomaly_timestamp), latest_anomaly_timestamp (maximum earliest_anomaly_timestamp), max_severity, median_severity, example_kpis (list of up to 5 strings formatted as \"kpi_name | earliest_anomaly_timestamp | severity\" showing that node's most severe KPIs). Sort the output by earliest_anomaly_timestamp ascending. Return all node rows (max 6). If no node-level anomalies exist, return a short note stating that. Limit output to this single compact table."
}

{
    "analysis": "We have completed metric/traces/logs thresholding and incident-window anomaly detection and produced a node-level summary. The node summary shows all nodes had anomalies during 2022-03-21 11:30–12:00, but node-6 and node-4 exhibit the largest max severities (node-6 max_severity=361.0; node-4 max_severity=300.5). Node-6 also shows anomalies continuing through the end of the incident window (latest_anomaly_timestamp up to 12:00). Per the diagnosis rules, the root-cause level is likely node-level (node anomalies show the largest deviations >>50%). To localize the root cause component (which pod/container on a node or the node itself), we must identify which containers/pods on node-6 show the most and earliest anomalous container-level KPIs tied to node-6. This will help decide whether node-6 is the single root cause and which pods were directly impacted first.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "From the cached metric_anomalies_df, filter rows where kpi_name contains the substring 'container.node-6'. Aggregate these filtered anomalies by cmdb_id (the container/pod name) and compute for each cmdb_id: distinct_kpi_count (number of distinct kpi_name values flagged), earliest_anomaly_timestamp (min), latest_anomaly_timestamp (max), max_severity, median_severity, and example_kpis (up to 5 of that cmdb_id's most severe kpi_name entries formatted as \"kpi_name | earliest_anomaly_timestamp | severity\"). Return the aggregated table sorted by distinct_kpi_count descending (then max_severity desc) and limit to top 20 rows. Also return a short count of how many distinct cmdb_id (pods/containers) are affected on node-6. Do not print raw time series."}

I reviewed the step-by-step analysis: thresholds, incident-window anomaly detection, node-level aggregations, container-level impacts on node-6, and trace/log correlations. Node-level KPI spikes (IO and network) were observed across nodes starting at 11:30, but the largest and most consequential spikes (system.io.r_s, system.io.rkb_s and many container node-6 network/IO KPIs) focused on node-6, with a clear critical IO spike at 2022-03-21 11:40:00 (UTC+8). Based on the severity, timing, and breadth of impacted containers and traces, I select node-6 and node disk read I/O consumption as the most likely root cause.

